<div id="content" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<h2 id="head-adc96d33e16b3c33dfbe2467aa7d6901f231572c">The Massive Iron Crown of Morgoth [0,+0]</h2>
<em>Two Silmarils of Feanor blaze from the thunderous crown of twisted iron. The corrupted metal feels at once as infernal as hellfire and as chilling as the Outer Darkness. One protrusion from the crown is abruptly ended where a third jewel might have shone.</em> <p>
It provides light (radius 1) forever. It increases your strength, intelligence, wisdom, dexterity, constitution, charisma and infravision by 125. It provides resistance to acid, electricity, fire , cold, poison, light, dark, confusion, nether and nexus. It allows you to see invisible monsters. It gives telepathic powers. It is permanently cursed. 
</p>
<h2 id="head-ff11f0da0a4cd245270f188d8a7299b4084d0328">Chatter</h2>
<strong><a href="./RedNaga">RedNaga</a></strong>: Just as a curiosity, but the +125 bonuses to stats are just to add to the feeling or they have some actual game effects? I.e. aren't the stats absolute maximums sets as 40, thus making rebundant such a huge bonus? <p>
<strong><a href="./ZasVid">ZasVid</a></strong>: Ummm, you get +125 to infravision, which is not limited! No redundancy, at all. Just kidding. I think that such a huge boni are to create a buffer for draining stats. It would take quite a long time to drain your stats below 40, wouldn't it? 
</p>

    <ul>

 <strong><a href="./RedNaga">RedNaga</a></strong>: +125 to infravision! I didn't think about that! Who need to light up levels anymore? :P . Same about kidding of course. And i think i understand the buffer thingy. I always thought that the maximum was applied before subtracting points lost due to draining, so the thing wasn't making any sense. Now it does. Thanks. 
    </ul>


<p>
<strong><a href="./MayLith">MayLith</a></strong>: Can you enchant it? And if you could, would you want to bother doing so? 
</p>
<p>
<a href="./NerdanelVampire">NerdanelVampire</a>: Artifacts can indeed be enchanted up (as I am won't to do with Sandworm's armor when I decide to wear it) and I don't know why Morgoth's crown would be an exception. The base fail rate is higher though so you need twice as many scrolls unless you get lucky. I guess you might want to enchant up the crown if you decide to wear it and go for the ultimate ending. Extra AC is never a bad thing although I'm unsure whether it stops benefiting you at some point. 
</p>
